+# Story 4.4: Virtual Scrolling & Column Prioritization
+
+Status: ready-for-dev
+
+> **Epic 4 ┬º 146-195** ┬À **FR12 (partial)** ┬À **UX-DR7** (FcColumnPrioritizer) ┬À **UX-DR42** (virtualization default + safety rails) ┬À **UX-DR63** (auto-generation scale limit at 15 fields) ┬À **NFR4** (DataGrid render P95 < 300ms on 500 rows) ┬À applies lessons **L01, L02, L03, L04, L06, L07, L09, L10, L11**. Consumes the Story 1-5 `ColumnModel` IR, Story 2-2 `GridViewSnapshot` (frozen schema ÔÇö including `ScrollTop` field already populated by the record's private setter), Story 3-6 `DataGridNavigationEffects` persistence layer (fail-closed per L03), Story 4-1 role-dispatched `EmitStandardDataGrid` shell, and Story 4-3 reserved-key packing convention for `GridViewSnapshot.Filters`. Provides the FIRST shipped producer of `ScrollTop` captures (turning Story 2-2's reserved field into a live write path) AND the FIRST consumer of a new `ColumnPriorityAttribute` IR path.
+
+---
+
+## Executive summary (Feynman-level, ~45 sec)
+
+Today every generated projection view renders `state.Items.AsQueryable()` into a bare `FluentDataGrid` without virtualization ÔÇö adopters whose projections hold 500+ rows see the browser stall because the render tree materialises every row up-front. Story 4-3 shipped filters/sort/search to narrow those sets, but a 10,000-row `OrdersProjection` with a "last 90 days" filter still returns 8,200 rows ÔÇö below any sensible filter-threshold but still large enough to blow the render budget. Story 4-4 closes that gap: **every generated view gains `Virtualize="true"` + `DisplayMode="Table"` + an `ItemSize`-tuned row budget + an `ItemsProvider` server-side lane for 500+ items** while Story 2-2's reserved `ScrollTop` field becomes live (scroll-position captured ÔåÆ persisted via the 3-6 effect ÔåÆ restored within-session).
+
+1. **Virtualize default ON.** `RazorEmitter.EmitStandardDataGrid` now emits `Virtualize="true"` + `DisplayMode="DataGridDisplayMode.Table"` + `ItemSize="{densityRowHeightPx}"` on every generated `FluentDataGrid` (D1 / D21 ÔÇö Table mode is the Fluent-recommended partner for `Virtualize`; Grid mode is known to exhibit scroll glitches per Fluent docs). The density-to-row-height mapping reuses Story 3-3's `DensityLevel` enum: `Compact=32px`, `Comfortable=44px`, `Roomy=56px`. The value is resolved at render time from the cascading `RenderContext.Density`, NOT at emit time (density is user-scoped, emit-time is compilation-scoped).
+2. **Client-side vs server-side lane.** For projections where `state.Items.Count < FcShellOptions.VirtualizationServerSideThreshold` (default `500`), the grid consumes `Items` directly ÔÇö client-side virtualization only renders visible rows plus `OverscanCount="3"` (D2). For counts at or above the threshold, the generated view routes through a `GridItemsProvider<T>` callback that dispatches `LoadPageAction(viewKey, skip, take, filters, sort, search)` and awaits `IState<LoadedPageState>.Value.PagesByKey[{viewKey, skip}]` ÔÇö the reducer accumulates fetched pages, and the callback resolves with the requested slice. ETag reuse is inherited from Story 1-5's `IQueryService.QueryAsync` via `QueryRequest.ETag` (no new cache layer).
+3. **Server-side pagination mechanics.** `GridItemsProvider<T>` signature is `Func<GridItemsProviderRequest<T>, ValueTask<GridItemsProviderResult<T>>>`. The generated view emits a provider method that (a) reads the hydrated filter/sort/search state from the Fluxor snapshot, (b) dispatches `LoadPageAction(viewKey, request.StartIndex, request.Count, filters, sort, search)`, (c) `await`s a `TaskCompletionSource<GridItemsProviderResult<T>>` the reducer signals when the page lands, (d) cancels pending awaits via `request.CancellationToken` flowing into `LoadPageAction` (D3). No new Fluxor effect ÔÇö `LoadPageAction` dispatches into the existing Story 1-5 `LoadAction`-adjacent service call with `QueryRequest.Skip` + `QueryRequest.Take` populated.
+4. **Scroll-position capture + restore.** The generated grid container carries a scroll-capture JS helper (D4) ÔÇö bound via `@onscroll` on the outer `div` hosting the grid. On scroll, the helper fires `ScrollCapturedEvent(viewKey, scrollTop)` through a 150 ms `TimeProvider`-anchored debounce (tighter than 4-3's 300 ms because scroll events fire 60 Hz). The reducer updates `GridViewSnapshot.ScrollTop` and chains `CaptureGridStateAction` so 3-6's persistence effect takes over. On view mount, the existing Story 4-3 `RestoreGridStateAction` dispatch (in `OnInitialized`) pulls the snapshot ÔÇö `ScrollTop` is applied via a JS interop `scrollToOffset(viewKey, top)` call AFTER the first render tick (D5 ÔÇö within-session restore only; cross-session is reset to 0 because hours-later scroll context is an anti-pattern).
+5. **FcColumnPrioritizer gate at 15 fields.** A new Shell component `FcColumnPrioritizer` wraps the `FluentDataGrid`'s column surface. When `model.Columns.Count > 15` (UX-DR63 / UX-DR7 trigger), the emitter wraps the grid's `ChildContent` in a priority-aware `@foreach` that renders ONLY the first 8-10 columns by priority (D6) and appends a `FluentButton Appearance="Outline"` labeled `"More columns ({N} hidden)"` at the end of the header row. Clicking the button opens a `FluentPopover` with a `FluentCheckbox` list of hidden columns; toggling a checkbox dispatches `ColumnVisibilityChangedAction(viewKey, columnKey, isVisible)`. Visibility writes back to `GridViewSnapshot.Filters["__hidden"]` as a CSV of hidden column names (D7 ÔÇö another reserved key, mirroring 4-3 D3 `__status`/`__search` packing ÔÇö no blob schema bump).
+6. **Column priority attribute.** New `[ColumnPriority(int)]` property-level attribute in Contracts, parsed by `AttributeParser` into `PropertyModel.ColumnPriority`. Lower-numbered = higher priority (1 = most important); unannotated properties get `int.MaxValue` and slot into declaration order after explicitly-prioritised columns. The transform stage (Story 1-5) sorts columns stable-by-priority-then-declaration-order when the count exceeds 15. HFC1028 (Information) fires when two columns share an explicit priority ÔÇö deterministic tiebreaker is declaration order.
+7. **Safety rails ÔÇö `MaxUnfilteredItems` + `SlowQueryThresholdMs`.** Two new `FcShellOptions` properties: `MaxUnfilteredItems` (int, default 10000) and `SlowQueryThresholdMs` (int, default 2000). When a projection's unfiltered page fetch returns exactly `MaxUnfilteredItems` items (server-capped), the generated view renders a `FluentMessageBar Intent="Info"` with the localised `MaxItemsCapNoticeTemplate` copy. When the first page fetch's elapsed time exceeds `SlowQueryThresholdMs`, the view renders a second `FluentMessageBar Intent="Info"` with the `SlowQueryNoticeMessage` copy ÔÇö the banner is auto-dismissing after 5 s (matches Story 2-4 `ConfirmedToastDurationMs` precedent). Measurement is `Stopwatch`-based inside the `LoadPageAction`-adjacent service call path (D8).
+8. **Row count header display.** When no filters are active, the view renders a simple `"{count} {entityPlural}"` (e.g. `"47 orders"`) above the grid. When filters ARE active, Story 4-3's `FcFilterSummary` already owns the `"{filteredCount} of {totalCount}"` display ÔÇö 4-4 does NOT duplicate. Count comes from `state.TotalCount` server-supplied per Story 4-3 D13 (D9 ÔÇö routing discipline: exactly one count surface visible at a time).
+
+The design honors the "capability contract" principle: `GridViewSnapshot` schema UNCHANGED (column visibility packed in reserved key, scroll position uses the already-reserved `ScrollTop` field), decisions land inside the L06 feature-story cap (Ôëñ 25 ÔÇö 4-4 targets 22), every cross-story seam is explicit (L01), and fail-closed tenant/user scoping is INHERITED unchanged from Story 3-6 per L03 (no new scope-check code). Scope is deliberately narrow: **virtualization + column prioritization + safety rails ÔÇö nothing else.** Expand-in-row (4.5), empty states (4.6), `FcNewItemIndicator` (Story 3-5 follow-up), and Epic 6 customization overrides are OUT of scope.
+
