+## Critical decisions (READ FIRST ÔÇö do NOT revisit)
+
+> **22 binding decisions.** Feature-story budget is Ôëñ 25 (L06). 4-4 lands at 22/25, leaving a 3-decision buffer for review rounds before Occam / Matrix trimming is required. Raise a spec-change proposal before revisiting any entry.
+
+| # | Decision | Rationale | Consumed by |
+|---|---|---|---|
+| **D1** | **`Virtualize="true"` is emitted on EVERY generated `FluentDataGrid` unconditionally** ÔÇö Default / ActionQueue / StatusOverview / Dashboard strategies (DetailRecord + Timeline do not emit `FluentDataGrid`). No opt-out, no per-projection annotation to disable. | UX-DR42 states virtualization is THE DEFAULT; opt-out surfaces proliferate code paths and give adopters rope to hang themselves with (a 50,000-row unvirtualized grid is the 0-user-actually-wants scenario). Virtualize-at-10-items is no slower than non-virtualize-at-10-items in Fluent v5 (verified via the Fluent team's benchmarks in the linked docs). Rejected: (a) activate when `Items.Count > N` ÔÇö two code paths to test, user sees different scroll behaviour before/after filtering; (b) `[NoVirtualize]` attribute ÔÇö negative-opt-out is an anti-pattern; (c) configurable via `FcShellOptions.EnableVirtualization` ÔÇö too coarse; Epic 6 Level 3 slot override handles the rare opt-out. | T2; AC1 |
+| **D2** | **`VirtualizationServerSideThreshold` (default 500) is the `Items.Count`-based runtime switch between client-side and server-side virtualization.** Below ÔåÆ `Items=state.Items.AsQueryable()`; at/above ÔåÆ `ItemsProvider=LoadPageAsync`. The generator emits BOTH paths and the runtime branch picks. | UX-DR42's "<500 client-side, 500+ server-side" maps 1:1 to a runtime comparison. Emitting both at emit time means the adopter doesn't need to recompile when their data volume crosses the threshold ÔÇö the switch is per-render. Rejected: (a) emit-time branch based on projection metadata ÔÇö projections don't know their runtime cardinality; (b) always server-side ÔÇö wastes a round-trip for 10-row projections; (c) always client-side with manual paging API ÔÇö contradicts UX-DR42 no-load-more discipline. | T2, T3; AC2 |
+| **D3** | **`GridItemsProvider<T>` is implemented as a private method on the generated class that dispatches `LoadPageAction` + awaits a `TaskCompletionSource<object>` registered by the effect.** The TCS lives in `LoadedPageState.PendingCompletionsByKey[(viewKey, skip)]`; the effect registers it synchronously BEFORE awaiting `IQueryService.QueryAsync` so races are impossible. The provider callback awaits `await Task.WhenAny(tcs.Task, cancellationTask)` ÔÇö cancellation from Fluent's scroll-away unwinds cleanly. | Fluxor-native ÔÇö every side effect goes through the action pipeline; no direct service access from the generated view. Rejected: (a) direct `IQueryService.QueryAsync` call from the provider ÔÇö bypasses Fluxor discipline, double-loads overlap with `LoadAction`; (b) `IObservable<GridItemsProviderResult<T>>` subscription ÔÇö heavier machinery for what is a one-shot request/response; (c) promise-per-page shared memoization dictionary ÔÇö the TCS pattern IS the memoization keyed by `(viewKey, skip)`. | T1, T3, T4; AC2 |
+| **D4** | **Scroll capture uses a 150 ms `TimeProvider`-anchored debounce on `@onscroll`** ÔÇö tighter than Story 4-3's 300 ms filter debounce because scroll events fire at ~60 Hz and a 300 ms debounce would feel laggy when the user stops scrolling. The debounce anchor is the injected `TimeProvider` (FakeTimeProvider in tests). Per-view `CancellationTokenSource`; on dispose the CTS cancels. | Schroeder's 100-200 ms "instant" threshold ÔÇö 150 ms is the midpoint. Reuses the Story 3-6 `TimeProvider.Delay(DebounceInterval, ct)` idiom. Rejected: (a) 300 ms to match 4-3 ÔÇö user-visible lag; (b) `requestAnimationFrame` batching ÔÇö JS-side complexity for no material win; (c) no debounce, dispatch every scroll ÔÇö 60 Hz dispatch storm; (d) capture on scroll-END only (`scrollend` event) ÔÇö only Chromium supports reliably, Safari/Firefox parity concerns. | T1, T4; AC7 |
+| **D5** | **Cross-session hydration of `GridViewSnapshot.ScrollTop` is CLAMPED to 0.** The reducer handling `GridViewHydratedAction` (defined in Story 2-2 / 3-6) is extended by 4-4 to zero-out `ScrollTop` before writing to `ViewStates`. Within-session dispatches ÔÇö `ScrollCapturedAction` ÔåÆ `CaptureGridStateAction` ÔåÆ existing 2-2 reducer ÔÇö pass through unchanged. | Restoring a scroll position from hours ago is disorienting ÔÇö the user has lost context, the data may have shifted (SignalR reconciliation in Epic 5 could have inserted rows), and there's nothing on screen to orient against. UX convention: scroll position is within-session only. Column-visibility is cross-session because it's a user PREFERENCE, not a transient pointer. Filter state is cross-session because it's a user INTENT, not a transient pointer. Rejected: (a) restore across sessions ÔÇö disorienting, no user research supports it; (b) restore with a confirmation prompt ÔÇö friction for a feature users don't ask for; (c) restore only when elapsed-since-capture < 1h ÔÇö arbitrary, still surprising; (d) restore only if the row count is unchanged ÔÇö requires pre-hydration count query, round-trip cost. | T2, T3, T4; AC6, AC7 |
+| **D6** | **`FcColumnPrioritizer` activates when `model.Columns.Count > 15` (strict greater-than; 15 columns is still bare-grid).** The first 10 columns by priority (D17 stable sort: `(Priority ?? int.MaxValue, DeclarationOrder)`) render by default; the remainder are hidden-by-default behind the "More columns" toggle. `MaxVisibleColumns=10` is hardcoded in the generator emission (UX-DR7 "first 8-10 columns" ÔÇö 10 is the high end, chosen to give adopters slightly more breathing room before the toggle is needed). | UX-DR63 uses "15 fields" as the trigger; strict `>` means "exactly 15 is fine, 16 triggers." 10 as the visible default balances UX-DR7's "8-10" range toward the user-forgiving end. Rejected: (a) trigger at `>=` 15 ÔÇö contradicts UX-DR63 literal reading; (b) `MaxVisibleColumns` exposed as an option ÔÇö adopters with "16 columns, show 12" is a rare case, Epic 6 template override handles it; (c) dynamic visible count based on viewport width ÔÇö Epic 10-2 responsive work. | T1, T2; AC5 |
+| **D7** | **Column visibility is packed into the existing `GridViewSnapshot.Filters` dictionary under the reserved key `__hidden`** (CSV of hidden column keys). Matches Story 4-3 D3 reserved-key pattern (`__status`, `__search`). No new field on `GridViewSnapshot`, no schema change to `GridViewPersistenceBlob`. | Single persistence surface means single serialisation surface means single test surface. The 4-3 `__` prefix convention is load-bearing ÔÇö 4-4 adds one more reserved key without breaking the contract. Column names starting with `__` are prevented by C# identifier rules (the adopter would need `@__hidden` to even declare such a property, and even then the generator emits property names without `@` ÔÇö collision at emit time requires pathological effort). Rejected: (a) add `HiddenColumns: EquatableArray<string>` field to `GridViewSnapshot` ÔÇö blob schema bump, cascades to `BlobSerializesToExpectedJsonShape` regen + persistence-blob migration; (b) separate dictionary `SpecialFilters: Dictionary<string, string>` ÔÇö doubles serialization surface; (c) JSON-encoded sub-state in a reserved `__meta` key ÔÇö opaque in LocalStorage devtools, hard to inspect. | T1, T2, T3, T4; AC5, AC6 |
+| **D8** | **Slow-query detection is `Stopwatch`-based inside `LoadPageEffect.HandleLoadPage`** ÔÇö measures elapsed time from effect entry to `IQueryService.QueryAsync` completion; emits `LoadPageSucceededAction.ElapsedMs`; the reducer writes into `LastElapsedMsByKey[viewKey]`. `FcSlowQueryNotice` subscribes and renders when the value exceeds `FcShellOptions.SlowQueryThresholdMs`. | In-effect measurement captures the user-observed latency (DI resolution + network + deserialization). Pushing into the component would miss the effect-resolution prefix. Rejected: (a) measure in the generated view via `DateTimeOffset.UtcNow` ÔÇö clock-skew concerns in WASM + cross-machine time jitter; `Stopwatch` is monotonic; (b) measure in `IQueryService` itself ÔÇö adopters may forget to surface; (c) measure via `Activity` spans ÔÇö overkill for a single metric, OpenTelemetry surface is Epic 5. | T3, T4; AC3, AC4 |
+| **D9** | **Row-count display is EMITTED above the grid but OWNED per-condition: Story 4-3's `FcFilterSummary` handles `{filteredCount} of {totalCount}` when filters are active; 4-4 renders a simpler `{count} {entityPlural}` label when filters are inactive.** The two are mutually exclusive ÔÇö the generator emits a runtime `@if (anyFilterActive) { <FcFilterSummary .../> } else { <span>@unfilteredLabel</span> }`. | Exactly one count surface visible at a time prevents the "3 of 47 and also 47 orders" confusion. Rejected: (a) always render 4-3's `FcFilterSummary` with a "no filter" mode ÔÇö pollutes 4-3's component contract; (b) always render 4-4's row-count label ÔÇö duplicates 4-3's count info when filtered; (c) no row-count display without filters ÔÇö loses the "47 orders" scannability signal. | T1, T2; AC4 |
+| **D10** | **Three new `FcShellOptions` properties: `MaxUnfilteredItems=10_000`, `SlowQueryThresholdMs=2_000`, `VirtualizationServerSideThreshold=500`.** Each gets a `[Range]` attribute constraining pathological values. `FcShellOptionsThresholdValidator` adds a cross-property invariant: `VirtualizationServerSideThreshold < MaxUnfilteredItems`. | Defaults match UX-spec `Pagination & Virtual Scrolling` literal values (10k / 2s / 500). `[Range]` prevents adopter misconfig from blowing up the runtime (e.g. `MaxUnfilteredItems=0` would show an empty grid always). Cross-property validator ensures the server-side lane triggers BEFORE the cap (otherwise the cap would be reached via a full-render path). Rejected: (a) hardcoded constants ÔÇö adopters whose infra can handle 100k rows need the override; (b) two options only (skip server-side threshold) ÔÇö conflates policy (`MaxUnfilteredItems` is infrastructure capacity) with mechanism (`VirtualizationServerSideThreshold` is UX lane-switch); (c) per-projection override via attribute ÔÇö Epic 6 customization territory. | T7, T8; AC3, AC4 |
